record.description: Folios 30-34: Surgeon's general remarks. Catarrhs were nearly double any other complaint. 13 cases of intermittent fever were entered, two of which were sent to hospital. According to the surgeon all of the ship's company were newly raised men and mostly came from Kent and Sussex. One case of diarrhoea occurred while the ship was cruising in the Channel and was sent to Haslar. A second Class boy was put on the list for rubeola on the 10 March 1855 and discharged to duty on 20 March 1855. The surgeon also stated that 8 cases of bronchitis were put on the list and discharged cured. The case of cholera occurred on the 18 December while the ship lay in [Kemasch?] Bay, and at that time the disease prevailed among the troops on shore, the patient Walter Smith, 31 Sick Berth Attendant, had cholera twice in England and though he recovered, had suffered so much from gastritis and bowel complaints that it was requisite to send him home. Also mentioned in the journal is a list of men killed and drowned on the 25 March 1854, Gebeon Batt Captain of the Mast fell over board in Keil Bay and drowned, King Marshal ordinary seaman was killed at Solovetskoi [Solovetsky?] on the 19 July, and Robert Kellar, ordinary seaman, by jumping over board in the White Sea on the 29 June 1854. The following invalids were brought from the White Sea to England, William Warren, sick berth attendant of HMS Brisk for [Lead?] paralysis, James Duncan, able seaman HMS Eurydice for scrofula, and Daniel O'Leary, Coastguard 'Eurydice' for asthma, in which he died suddenly on the passage home. The surgeon also makes reference to [Grant's?] distilling galley in use on board this ship which produced an abundance of water which was not only wholesome but also palatable. Also the surgeon describes the topography and natural history of the White Sea. Includes arguments on desirability of substituting French compressed cabbage for preserved potatoes to combat scurvy (folio 33).

Scope and Content

This series is an accumulation of miscellaneous maps. It includes examples of maps of which publication has now ceased and maps of surveys undertaken by the Ordnance Survey outside the normal run of the department's work: the latter are in most cases not preserved elsewhere.

The series of maps of roads, railways, and traffic and transport areas prepared for the London Passenger Transport Board in 1933 and 1936 are based on the one-inch Popular Series.

The series includes material which would otherwise be found amongst the Records of the Chief of the (Imperial) General Staff and its directorates (WO).
